  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Prison Sentences\n- Up to 20 years for each money laundering offense\n- Maximum of 30 years if the laundering involves proceeds from certain serious crimes\n\n2. Significant Financial Penalties\n- Fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater\n\n3. Asset Forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets connected to the laundered funds\n- Property, bank accounts, and other financial instruments may be confiscated\n\n4. Additional Consequences\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Significant damage to personal and professional reputation\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n5. Civil Penalties\n- Potential civil monetary penalties in addition to criminal charges\n\nSpecific penalties can vary based on:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific criminal statute violated\n- Individual's criminal history\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n\nThese penalties are typically prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and related federal statutes.\n\nNote: This is general information and not legal advice. Actual penalties depend on specific case details and judicial interpretation.",
